In article <1993Dec13.204000.4737@cc.ic.ac.uk> pjc@cc.ic.ac.uk (Peter Churchyard) writes:
>I have proposed to my management that we put together a challenge/response
>system for authenticiation of telnet/pop etc based on the PEM structures
>
>DEK-Info and Key-Info
>
>Basically having got the username, the service generates a new DES key and
>uses the PEM encodings to return it to the user, whose access unit, decrypts
>it using their private key and re-encrypts it using the services public key
>and sends it back. 
>
>Once the service end has decrypted the returned data, it knows that the user
>knows the users private key and they now have a DES key that they can use
>for comunications privacy. Are any of the telnet options available for
>negociation of privacy?

Keep in mind that doing RSA decryption takes a *lot* of computation.

If you don't mind stored secrets in your network (perhaps just on a
single server), why not just use Kerberos?  It does everything you want,
and it's free.
